Figure a. Wickelfeature dictionary with regularization, N=1000. We evaluate the network's
performance by comparing the output to the correct answer and measuring the similarity in the
feature space. We see that words in the training set start with high similarity and remain
high (blue), indicating one-shot learning. Words in the test set increase as more words are added in
the training set and common transformations are found and applied.
Figure b. Wickelfeature dictionary with regularization, N=10000.
Figure c. Wickelfeature dictionary, N=1000. We evaluated the performance of the network by
comparing the network's output to the Wickelfeature representation of the correct word. We see
that all words in the training set have high similarity (blue line), but also that the similarity
increases beyond the normal level. We also see that as more verb pairs are encountered that words
in the test set also increase in similarity to the correct answer in the feature space.
Figure d. Wickelfeature dictionary, N=10000.
Figure e. Wickelfeature difference dictionary with regularization, N=1000. We use the difference
algorithm with regularization and see that words in the training set have high similarity
throughout. Words in the test set start off with some similarity and increase. N=1000.
Figure f. Wickelfeature difference dictionary with regularization, N=10000.
Figure g. Wickelfeature difference dictionary, N=1000. The algorithm that stores the transform
immediately has some similarity with words in the test set, because the present-tense word is
usually similar to the past-tense word without any transformation. We again see the over-emphasis
of certain transformation features, leading to similarities going above N.
Figure h. Wickelfeature difference dictionary, N=10000.
